}
@misc{Jensen1996,
abstract = {Determined whether the model for storage and recall of sequence information (O. Jensen and J. E. Lisman, see record 84-24910) can account for some key results regarding hippocampal place cells (PCs). It is shown that the phase advance can be understood if it is assumed that the hippocampus is in a recall mode that operates when a rat is already familiar with a path. In this mode, sensory information about the current position triggers recall of the upcoming 5–6 places in the path at a rate of 1 memory per gamma cycle. The model predicts that the average phase advance will be 1 gamma cycle per theta cycle. The model also accounts for the fact that the firing of a PC occurs during ≈7 theta cycles (on average) as a rat crosses the place field; the observation that the phase of PC firing depends more systematically on position than on time; and the fact that traversal of an already familiar path produces further modifications. This later finding suggests that recall of previously stored information strengthens the memory of that information. The general success of the model provides support for the idea that the hippocampus stores sequence information and makes predictions of expected positions during gamma-frequency recall. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2017 APA, all rights reserved)},
